</div>
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Bhabani Bhattacharya</h1>
									<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
									<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><table class="infobox vcard" style="width:22em">
<tr>
<th colspan="2" style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold"><span class="fn">Bhabani Bhattacharya</span></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row" style="padding-top:0.225em;line-height:1.1em;padding-right:0.65em;">Born</th>
<td style="line-height:1.4em;"><span style="display:none">(<span class="bday">1906-11-10</span>)</span>10 November 1906<br />
<a href="/wiki/Bhagalpur" title="Bhagalpur">Bhagalpur</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bengal_Presidency" title="Bengal Presidency">Bengal Presidency</a>, <a href="/wiki/British_India" title="British India" class="mw-redirect">British India</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row" style="padding-top:0.225em;line-height:1.1em;padding-right:0.65em;">Died</th>
<td style="line-height:1.4em;">10 October 1988<span style="display:none">(<span class="dday deathdate">1988-10-10</span>)</span> (aged&#160;81)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row" style="padding-top:0.225em;line-height:1.1em;padding-right:0.65em;">Occupation</th>
<td class="role" style="line-height:1.4em;">Writer</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<th scope="row" style="padding-top:0.225em;line-height:1.1em;padding-right:0.65em;">Period</th>
<td style="line-height:1.4em;">20th century</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Bhabani Bhattacharya</b> (10 November 1906–10 October 1988) was an <a href="/wiki/Indian_literature" title="Indian literature">Indian writer</a>, of <a href="/wiki/Bengali_people" title="Bengali people" class="mw-redirect">Bengali</a> origin, who wrote social-realist fiction. He was born in <a href="/wiki/Bhagalpur" title="Bhagalpur">Bhagalpur</a>, part of the <a href="/wiki/Bengal_Presidency" title="Bengal Presidency">Bengal Presidency</a> in <a href="/wiki/British_India" title="British India" class="mw-redirect">British India</a>. Bhattacharya gained a bachelor's degree from <a href="/wiki/Patna_University" title="Patna University">Patna University</a> and a doctorate from the <a href="/wiki/University_of_London" title="University of London">University of London</a>. He returned to India and joined the diplomatic service. Bhattacharya served in the <a href="/wiki/USA" title="USA" class="mw-redirect">USA</a>, to which country he returned as a teacher of literary studies once he had left the service. He taught in Hawaii, and later in Seattle. In his mid-thirties Bhattacharya began writing fiction set in historically and socially realistic contexts. He wrote in English, his chosen medium following the advice of two prominent literary figures.</p>
<p></p>
